quot;are safe and feel safe&quot;. A few children are either obviously unsafe or disclose that they are being abused at school (both of which applied to Khyra Ishaq and her siblings). If they are lucky, the school passes the information on (as in this case) to a Social Services department that can help them (the tragic failing in this case is that Birmingham SS staff were too overworked and undertrained to deal with the referral appropriately). &#10;I do not pay taxes in order to have government check up on me as I go about my lawful business. OTOH, if someone thinks I may not be acting lawfully, the authorities can and should follow up. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="931" language="en" documentId="1125" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Shena" date="29 July 2010 8:11am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6873673" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="10" thumbsDown="0" origId="1125" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="13"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="14" end="100"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="101" end="738"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="739" end="931"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>